        "Description": {
            "val": "This program provides a combination of US Navy projects planned to counter the threat to amphibious landing forces from known and projected foreign land\/sea mines, obstacles in the Beach Zone (BZ) and Surf Zone (SZ) approaches to amphibious assault areas.  It is a system of systems (Countermine\/Counter Obstacle, Intelligence\/Surveillance\/Reconnaissance\/Targeting (ISR\/T), Navigation\/Virtual Marking\/Integration, C4I\/Data Fusion) that provides a full assault breaching capability.  This program is an essential element to the Marine Corps Ship To Objective Maneuver Concept of Operations.\n\n[P5 \/ SW004: COASTAL BATTLEFIELD RECONNAISSANCE AND ANALYSIS (COBRA)]: The mission of the AN\/DVS-1 COBRA is to conduct unmanned aerial tactical reconnaissance in the littoral battlespace for detection and localization of minefields and obstacles in the surf zone and beach zone prior to an amphibious assault. The COBRA airborne payload is carried on the MQ-8 Fire Scout Vertical Takeoff and Landing Unmanned Aerial Vehicle\n(VTUAV). This allows operators and other personnel to remain at a safe distance from the mine and obstacle belts as well as enemy direct and indirect fire. COBRA will be embarked in the Littoral Combat Ship (LCS) as part of the\nMine Countermeasures (MCM) Mission Package (MP).\n\nCOBRA provides the ISR\/T part of the Assault Breaching System (ABS) of systems. One system consists of two COBRA Airborne Payload Subsystem (CAPS) and one Post Mission Analysis (PMA) station. Block I introduced a\ndaytime detection capability for surface laid minefields and obstacles in the Beach Zone. Additional capabilities to include a daytime surf zone, very shallow water and shallow water detection capability will be introduced via\nengineering changes through FY24. COBRA has a modular payload architecture, is integrated with the MQ-8 Fire Scout VTUAV and other vessels of opportunity, and in its expeditionary configuration from the shore. COBRA\nserves as a Coastal Mine Reconnaissance (CMR) sensor within the LCS MCM MP as part of amphibious assault breaching mission.\n\nThe OPN 2624 procurement line supports the COBRA program of record, delivering COBRA systems to Navy helicopter wings to provide initial proficiency training to Navy aircrews. The OPN 1601 procurement line supports the systems that provide the deployable combat capability to LCS mission packages."
        },
        "Justification": {
            "val": "FY 2021 funding supports engineering updates for system maintenance (e.g. Cybersecurity), obsolescence mitigation of CAPS\/PMA subsystem components and expected system enhancements to improve the probability of\ndetection, reduce false alarms and improve searching Concept of Operations in the BZ. Additional capabilities to include a daytime a surf zone, very shallow water and shallow water detection capability will be\nintroduced via engineering changes through FY24."
        },
